issue_body:
Another C++11 feature yields a token exception: Trailing return types in function declarations.

#### Error Message
>Got exception in MyClass.h @ Token('auto', 41, 45) []
>Got exception in MyClass.h @ Token('class', 14, 19) []
>MyClass.h: parsing error (Token('->', 68, 70), [Token('auto', 41, 45)], [Token('double', 50, 56), Token('const', 57, 62), Token('&', 63, 64), Token('t', 65, 66)])

#### Code Example
````c++
#pragma once

class CMyClass
{
public:
  auto Foo(double const & t) -> int {
    return 42;
  }
};
````

	@asyncio.coroutine
	def send(self, conversation, message, image=None):
		yield from conversation.send_message(hangups.ChatMessageSegment.from_str(message), image_file=image)

Currently, the filepath of the image is being passed to send(), but neither the message nor the image is sending. However, if no image_file is passed, a message is sent. Does send_message support image sending or is there another way to implement this? Sorry if this is a duplicate.

https://gist.github.com/kurtbrose/8633b06f0bced5cba52a7a8b1d763ae8

```python
    @validate_args(a=[str], b=int, c=lambda v: v is not None)
    def foo(a, b, c, d):
        return a, b, c, d

    try:
        foo('cat', 1, 2, 3)
    except ValueError as ve:
        print ve

    try:
        foo([1], b=2, c=None, d=12)
    except ValueError as ve:
        print ve
    
    foo(['cat', 'dog'], 2, 3, 4)
```

Intercepts kwargs passed to `@validate_args()` and passes them through the validate() of the corresponding schema before being passed on to the wrapped function.

Failed validates are gathered together and raised as a single exception.

