It seems on a python3 we systematically use SQLDirectW to execute a query on the driver.
```

        szLastFunction = "SQLExecDirect";
#if PY_MAJOR_VERSION < 3
        if (PyString_Check(pSql))
        {
            Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
            ret = SQLExecDirect(cur->hstmt, (SQLCHAR*)PyString_AS_STRING(pSql), SQL_NTS);
            Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
        }
        else
#endif
        {
            SQLWChar query(pSql);
            if (!query)
                return 0;
            Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
            ret = SQLExecDirectW(cur->hstmt, query.get(), SQL_NTS);
            Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
        }
```

Why do we systematically expect "UTF-16" input ?

An example is provided in the docs for supporting global filters with context:

```py
@library.filter
@jinja2.contextfilter
def replace(context, value, x, y):
    """
    Filter with template context. Usage: {{ 'Hello'|replace('H','M') }}
    """
    return value.replace(x, y)
```

Based on this I expect this to work:

```py
@library.global_function
@jinja2.contextfunction
def breadcrumb(*args, **kwargs):
    return django_bootstrap_breadcrumbs.breadcrumb(*args, **kwargs)
```

Alas it doesn't, and as as I can tell it's not implemented? Anyone point in the right direction and/or is this a feasible feature to add if I'm right and it is absent?

Hope I am not overlooking something, but whenever I use "require" for some custom installed nodejs module, I get an exception `execjs._exceptions.ProgramError: Error: Cannot find module`. Is it for instance necessary to set paths somehow where modules would be searched?

Simple test case with one module, [fastrpc](https://github.com/seznam/node-fastrpc):

Install the module `npm install fastrpc`

Try this python code to invoke pyexecjs to invoke the module:

    #!/usr/bin/env python
    import execjs
    print "Engine name", execjs.get().name
    
    code = """
    var fastrpc = require('fastrpc');
    
    function frpc2json(string) {
        var buffer = new Buffer(string, 'base64');
        var bufferArray = new Uint8Array(buffer);
        var decoded = fastrpc.parse(bufferArray);
        return  JSON.stringify(decoded);
    }
    """
    
    ctx = execjs.compile(code)
    res = ctx.call("frpc2json", 'yhECAWgRdXNlci5saXN0TWVzc2FnZXM7L1wfASAMbGFiZWwtaWQ6MjU4QAA4ZA==')
    print res

Result:

    Engine name Node.js (V8)
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "./cant_resolve_modules.py", line 17, in <module>
        res = ctx.call("frpc2json", 'yhECAWgRdXNlci5saXN0TWVzc2FnZXM7L1wfASAMbGFiZWwtaWQ6MjU4QAA4ZA==')
      File "/home/ondro/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/execjs/_abstract_runtime_context.py", line 37, in call
        return self._call(name, *args)
      File "/home/ondro/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/execjs/_external_runtime.py", line 87, in _call
        return self._eval("{identifier}.apply(this, {args})".format(identifier=identifier, args=args))
      File "/home/ondro/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/execjs/_external_runtime.py", line 73, in _eval
        return self.exec_(code)
      File "/home/ondro/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/execjs/_abstract_runtime_context.py", line 18, in exec_
        return self._exec_(source)
      File "/home/ondro/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/execjs/_external_runtime.py", line 83, in _exec_
        return self._extract_result(output)
      File "/home/ondro/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/execjs/_external_runtime.py", line 165, in _extract_result
        raise exceptions.ProgramError(value)
    execjs._exceptions.ProgramError: Error: Cannot find module 'fastrpc'

I've found some unexpected (to me) behaviour in WTForms-JSON where an empty string in an optional string field with a minimum length did not result in a validation error nor exclusion of the field from patch_data. I've written a small [test script](https://gist.github.com/kshade/a9a2e9ba514461bdbf02e17ce0ea4b1a), here is the output I'm getting from it:

```
WTForms-JSON version 0.3.3

json {}
errors {}
form.data {'name': None}
form.patch_data {}

json {'name': ''}
errors {}
form.data {'name': None}
form.patch_data {'name': None}

json {'name': 'a'}
errors {'name': ['Field must be between 2 and 128 characters long.']}
form.data {'name': 'a'}
form.patch_data {'name': 'a'}

json {'name': 'ab'}
errors {}
form.data {'name': 'ab'}
form.patch_data {'name': 'ab'}
```

Length validation doesn't happen with the second test case, but it also isn't removed from patch_data like in the first.

I've encountered two big issues when attempting to make relatively simple use of this Eve backend. First, it seems items are not available at their endpoint: "/{resource}/{_id}". And second, it seems that only GET requests work. 

With issues this obvious, I'm inclined to say that I'm using this wrong. So, below is a simple setup that replicates the issues:

```python
# settings.py

RESOURCE_METHODS = ['GET','POST']
ITEM_METHODS = ['GET','PUT','PATCH','DELETE']
PUBLIC_RESOURCE_METHODS = ['GET','POST']
PUBLIC_ITEM_METHODS = ['GET','PUT','PATCH','DELETE']

DOMAIN = {
    'test': {
        'schema': {
            'foo': {
                'type': 'string'
            } 
        },
        'datasource': {
            'backend': 'elastic'
        }
    }
}
```

```python
# app.py
from eve_elastic import Elastic
from eve import Eve

Eve(data=Elastic).run()
```

Also, here is a quick demostration with curl:

```bash
$ # POST a resource
$ curl -XPOST -H 'Content-Type: application/json' localhost:5000/test -d '{foo: bar}'
{
  "_status": "OK",
  "_updated": "Sat, 16 May 2015 20:25:53 GMT",
